1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,480
 So there was this moment that happened for me

2
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:06,800
 on my recent walk of the Camino de Santiago in Spain

3
00:00:06,800 --> 00:00:10,560
 that deeply reminds me of what we have just been

4
00:00:10,560 --> 00:00:13,040
 singing about in that song.

5
00:00:13,040 --> 00:00:16,500
 The Camino is around about 800 kilometers of length.

6
00:00:16,500 --> 00:00:19,880
 You walk from this place called Saint John in France

7
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:22,260
 all the way to Santiago de Compostela

8
00:00:22,260 --> 00:00:24,000
 in the west coast of Spain.

9
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:26,920
 And as you walk every day, you connect to

10
00:00:26,920 --> 00:00:30,880
 and walk through and past multiple Catholic churches.

11
00:00:30,880 --> 00:00:33,520
 In fact, on any particular given day,

12
00:00:33,520 --> 00:00:36,840
 you might walk through say three to five different villages

13
00:00:36,840 --> 00:00:38,340
 and every single one of those villages

14
00:00:38,340 --> 00:00:40,880
 will be centered around some form of church,

15
00:00:40,880 --> 00:00:42,320
 this Catholic church.

16
00:00:42,320 --> 00:00:46,040
 And some of those churches are incredibly beautiful,

17
00:00:46,040 --> 00:00:50,120
 huge, wonderful buildings, like architectural wonders.

18
00:00:50,120 --> 00:00:53,200
 Some of those churches are small, rural,

19
00:00:53,200 --> 00:00:56,320
 almost forgotten churches where maybe inside

20
00:00:56,320 --> 00:00:58,520
 there is nothing more than a couple of pews

21
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:02,360
 and a rusty old iron cross.

22
00:01:02,360 --> 00:01:05,600
 And I used to love when I was walking the Camino

23
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:08,500
 to take every opportunity I could to connect with a church.

24
00:01:08,500 --> 00:01:10,720
 If I was walking past a church,

25
00:01:10,720 --> 00:01:13,360
 inevitably those churches would be open.

26
00:01:13,360 --> 00:01:16,440
 And most of the time, they were open and no one was in there

27
00:01:16,440 --> 00:01:19,520
 and so I loved that because it meant that I could go in,

28
00:01:19,520 --> 00:01:22,340
 have a time of solitude, maybe take my backpack off

29
00:01:22,340 --> 00:01:25,360
 for 10 minutes and just sit there and pray

30
00:01:25,360 --> 00:01:27,280
 and encounter the presence of God.

31
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:30,120
 These churches were like wonderful gifts of solitude

32
00:01:30,120 --> 00:01:31,920
 as we walked every day.

33
00:01:31,920 --> 00:01:33,640
 Well, on this particular day,

34
00:01:33,640 --> 00:01:35,920
 I was walking into this small village

35
00:01:35,920 --> 00:01:38,080
 and I noticed that there was a church

36
00:01:38,080 --> 00:01:39,400
 that was off the trail.

37
00:01:39,400 --> 00:01:43,360
 Now, this was somewhat unusual because usually the Camino,

38
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:46,700
 the official trail, takes you to the center of a village

39
00:01:46,700 --> 00:01:49,480
 or the center of a town and right up to the big church

40
00:01:49,480 --> 00:01:50,700
 in the center of the town.

41
00:01:50,700 --> 00:01:52,760
 But for whatever reason, in this particular village,

42
00:01:52,760 --> 00:01:54,960
 the Camino path was going straight ahead

43
00:01:54,960 --> 00:01:58,960
 and avoiding the little church that was over to the left.

44
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:01,480
 And I saw it would take me maybe about five or seven minutes

45
00:02:01,480 --> 00:02:04,440
 to walk over to that church and I had time

46
00:02:04,440 --> 00:02:06,840
 and so I decided, okay, look, I'm gonna go off the path,

47
00:02:06,840 --> 00:02:09,520
 I'm gonna go over there and I'm going to just have my time

48
00:02:09,520 --> 00:02:11,100
 of solitude in this church.

49
00:02:11,100 --> 00:02:12,560
 So I enter into this church.

50
00:02:12,560 --> 00:02:13,800
 It's a small church.

51
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:15,880
 It's probably got about, maybe it could seat

52
00:02:15,880 --> 00:02:18,800
 maybe 50 people in total, so a small kind of church.

53
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:21,360
 As I walk straight in, I'm the only person there

54
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:23,800
 or at least I thought I was, but as soon as I walk in,

55
00:02:23,800 --> 00:02:26,720
 I hear this kind of like person get up from sitting down

56
00:02:26,720 --> 00:02:29,760
 over on the right side and it's this old nun

57
00:02:29,760 --> 00:02:33,720
 and she runs up to me with this big smile on her face

58
00:02:33,720 --> 00:02:37,960
 and she's so excited that a pilgrim has entered the church.

59
00:02:37,960 --> 00:02:40,400
 I could tell from her face that she's been waiting

60
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:45,080
 a long time for someone to come and visit her in her church

61
00:02:45,080 --> 00:02:46,920
 and she's got this big smile on her face

62
00:02:46,920 --> 00:02:49,760
 and she literally runs up to me and she grabs my arms

63
00:02:49,760 --> 00:02:52,880
 with her little hands and she starts speaking to me

64
00:02:52,880 --> 00:02:54,600
 excitedly in Spanish.

65
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:58,780
 Now, if you know me, you'll know I know nothing

66
00:02:58,780 --> 00:03:01,200
 of Spanish at all, but in that moment,

67
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:05,140
 I could see her enthusiasm and her joy that I had visited,

68
00:03:05,140 --> 00:03:07,500
 so I didn't want to break her heart by telling her

69
00:03:07,500 --> 00:03:09,260
 I didn't speak Spanish.

70
00:03:09,260 --> 00:03:12,520
 So I just let her talk and as she talked,

71
00:03:12,520 --> 00:03:15,940
 I followed her nonverbal cues as to pretend

72
00:03:15,940 --> 00:03:18,500
 that I understood her, so if she smiled,

73
00:03:18,500 --> 00:03:19,720
 I would be like, oh.

74
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:23,360
 If she nodded, I would be like, mm.

75
00:03:23,360 --> 00:03:26,720
 And I basically was trying to pretend like,

76
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:28,000
 I think probably after a while,

77
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:29,640
 she realized I couldn't speak Spanish,

78
00:03:29,640 --> 00:03:33,000
 but anyway, she kept going and she was so enthusiastic,

79
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,180
 so excited, she grabbed me on the arm

80
00:03:35,180 --> 00:03:37,220
 and she started to walk me through her church.

81
00:03:37,220 --> 00:03:39,140
 Now, again, it's not a particularly big church,

82
00:03:39,140 --> 00:03:43,280
 but there were like paintings and icons all over this church

83
00:03:43,280 --> 00:03:45,120
 as there often are in Catholic churches

84
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:47,960
 and so she wanted to like show me and tell me

85
00:03:47,960 --> 00:03:52,800
 in incredibly detailed Spanish all about these paintings

86
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:56,080
 and the icons and so I'm polite and I'm nice

87
00:03:56,080 --> 00:03:58,040
 and so I'm following her along and nodding

88
00:03:58,040 --> 00:04:00,200
 at the right times and laughing at the right time.

89
00:04:00,200 --> 00:04:03,320
 We get about halfway around and by this time,

90
00:04:03,320 --> 00:04:05,400
 we're standing at the front where the kind of nave

91
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:07,640
 of the church is and we're standing there

92
00:04:07,640 --> 00:04:10,520
 and she's talking away and we hear somebody else

93
00:04:10,520 --> 00:04:12,560
 enter the church and so we both kind of turn

94
00:04:12,560 --> 00:04:14,520
 and sure enough, in the entrance of the church,

95
00:04:14,520 --> 00:04:16,560
 another pilgrim walks in.

96
00:04:16,560 --> 00:04:18,960
 Now, this pilgrim, you can tell he's a pilgrim

97
00:04:18,960 --> 00:04:20,720
 'cause he's wearing his backpack and everything,

98
00:04:20,720 --> 00:04:23,880
 looks like a pilgrim, he's probably in his late 50s,

99
00:04:23,880 --> 00:04:27,740
 early 60s and he comes in and he stands literally inside

100
00:04:27,740 --> 00:04:31,160
 the entrance of the church and he starts to weep.

101
00:04:31,160 --> 00:04:33,960
 Now, this is not just like your standard

102
00:04:33,960 --> 00:04:36,440
 kind of like a couple of tears, a little bit embarrassed,

103
00:04:36,440 --> 00:04:39,220
 sort of don't really mean to be crying here at the moment

104
00:04:39,220 --> 00:04:44,220
 kind of tears, this was like a wailing kind of mourning,

105
00:04:44,700 --> 00:04:48,240
 kind of gnashing of teeth, kind of very loud

106
00:04:48,240 --> 00:04:51,880
 sort of sobbing that this man was doing.

107
00:04:51,880 --> 00:04:55,600
 The nun stares up at me and her eyes are filled

108
00:04:55,600 --> 00:04:58,760
 with this beautiful picture of compassion

109
00:04:58,760 --> 00:05:01,720
 and she leaves me straight away and I don't know

110
00:05:01,720 --> 00:05:04,180
 if you have ever seen a nun run.

111
00:05:04,180 --> 00:05:07,100
 But if you ever get the chance to see a nun run,

112
00:05:07,100 --> 00:05:09,040
 I highly recommend it.

113
00:05:09,040 --> 00:05:12,400
 She leaves me and she hitches up like the skirt

114
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:15,740
 of her habit and she runs down the center of the church

115
00:05:15,740 --> 00:05:16,980
 to this man.

116
00:05:16,980 --> 00:05:21,160
 She runs up to him and embraces him in this big hug

117
00:05:21,160 --> 00:05:23,560
 and then she gingerly and tenderly walks him

118
00:05:23,560 --> 00:05:25,940
 and sits him down in one of the pews

119
00:05:25,940 --> 00:05:27,720
 and she begins to pray for him.

120
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:32,220
 And there is this profound moment that something

121
00:05:32,220 --> 00:05:35,020
 is happening in this little church that no one

122
00:05:35,020 --> 00:05:39,820
 perhaps expected and that moment of great compassion

123
00:05:39,820 --> 00:05:43,260
 of hers and the running towards the one in need

124
00:05:43,260 --> 00:05:45,900
 filled and stirred compassion in me.

125
00:05:45,900 --> 00:05:48,240
 And I remember feeling to myself like I just came in here

126
00:05:48,240 --> 00:05:50,640
 to connect with Jesus but actually now is a chance

127
00:05:50,640 --> 00:05:53,740
 for me to be pastoral and so I walked, I didn't run,

128
00:05:53,740 --> 00:05:57,680
 I walked down the church and I came up against the man

129
00:05:57,680 --> 00:06:00,280
 and I just gently placed my hand on his shoulder

130
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:03,460
 and I began to pray and the nun is praying fervently

131
00:06:03,460 --> 00:06:07,380
 for him and he's loudly wailing and crying

132
00:06:07,380 --> 00:06:11,500
 and I didn't know anything about this man at that moment

133
00:06:11,500 --> 00:06:15,220
 but a few days later I discovered that he was

134
00:06:15,220 --> 00:06:19,260
 a Portuguese man and he had been a homicide detective

135
00:06:19,260 --> 00:06:22,620
 for 20 years and he was walking the Camino

136
00:06:22,620 --> 00:06:25,420
 just as he is retired, he's walking the Camino

137
00:06:25,420 --> 00:06:29,300
 to purge the evil that he had seen out of himself

138
00:06:29,300 --> 00:06:30,360
 over 20 years.

139
00:06:30,360 --> 00:06:34,620
 And something happened in that moment where he walks

140
00:06:34,620 --> 00:06:38,260
 into that church, the Holy Spirit meets with him

141
00:06:38,260 --> 00:06:41,380
 and we have this profound encounter together

142
00:06:41,380 --> 00:06:45,260
 and as we're standing there praying over him,

143
00:06:45,260 --> 00:06:49,340
 we're praying in human languages that are mixed

144
00:06:49,340 --> 00:06:53,060
 and only partially understood but we're also praying

145
00:06:53,060 --> 00:06:56,660
 in a heart and emotional language that is clear

146
00:06:56,660 --> 00:06:59,420
 and fully understood, perhaps more understood

147
00:06:59,420 --> 00:07:03,460
 than any other language can be and that's the universal

148
00:07:03,460 --> 00:07:07,160
 language of unadulterated love.

149
00:07:07,160 --> 00:07:09,860
 Love.

150
00:07:09,860 --> 00:07:14,460
 I wonder if you've ever tried to describe love

151
00:07:14,460 --> 00:07:18,780
 or try to find words to explain to somebody what love is.

152
00:07:18,780 --> 00:07:21,100
 It's actually really hard, isn't it, to kind of use

153
00:07:21,100 --> 00:07:25,180
 language to try to describe a factual or logical

154
00:07:25,180 --> 00:07:28,160
 understanding of what love is but when we're swept up

155
00:07:28,160 --> 00:07:32,780
 in a moment of love, when love breaks through barriers

156
00:07:32,780 --> 00:07:35,460
 and begins to do what only love can do,

157
00:07:35,460 --> 00:07:39,580
 well it lifts something in us as human beings, doesn't it?

158
00:07:39,580 --> 00:07:44,520
 It creates something within us and it binds us together

159
00:07:44,520 --> 00:07:49,020
 as humans like nothing ever can where three strangers

160
00:07:49,020 --> 00:07:52,220
 who don't even speak the same language can find

161
00:07:52,220 --> 00:07:55,500
 a deeper connection than in any other time.

162
00:07:55,500 --> 00:08:00,260
 When love breaks through, humans become just the way

163
00:08:00,260 --> 00:08:02,020
 they were created to be.

164
00:08:03,020 --> 00:08:05,380
 It's interesting, I wonder if you've ever thought

165
00:08:05,380 --> 00:08:10,380
 of love that way, that love actually makes us truly human,

166
00:08:10,380 --> 00:08:15,100
 that the moments of pure love are our most natural

167
00:08:15,100 --> 00:08:18,160
 and rawest moments as human beings.

168
00:08:18,160 --> 00:08:21,300
 There's a lot of talk right now about AI

169
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:23,820
 and about the future of AI and particularly about

170
00:08:23,820 --> 00:08:28,260
 the future of humanity swept up in this kind of formation

171
00:08:28,260 --> 00:08:31,100
 and forming and shaping of what humanity will look like

172
00:08:31,100 --> 00:08:34,180
 in the future because of AI and I think there's a lot

173
00:08:34,180 --> 00:08:37,420
 of things to be excited for with this development of AI

174
00:08:37,420 --> 00:08:40,640
 as well as perhaps some things for us to be cautious about

175
00:08:40,640 --> 00:08:43,540
 but here's one thing I do know, there is one thing

176
00:08:43,540 --> 00:08:46,820
 that no matter how advanced AI may become,

177
00:08:46,820 --> 00:08:51,180
 it will never be able to do and that is to love.

178
00:08:51,180 --> 00:08:56,700
 You see, I'm convinced that love is our unique contribution

179
00:08:56,700 --> 00:09:00,020
 to the world that sets us apart as human beings

180
00:09:00,020 --> 00:09:02,180
 who are made in the image of God.

181
00:09:02,180 --> 00:09:05,100
 Isn't that a beautiful thought?

182
00:09:05,100 --> 00:09:08,980
 That love might be the one thing that sets us apart,

183
00:09:08,980 --> 00:09:12,060
 that love might be the unique thing that has been placed

184
00:09:12,060 --> 00:09:15,100
 inside of us to help us to contribute something

185
00:09:15,100 --> 00:09:17,940
 to this incredible creation that God has made.

186
00:09:17,940 --> 00:09:22,220
 Could it be that love is able to do what no algorithm

187
00:09:22,220 --> 00:09:24,480
 could ever predict or do?

188
00:09:24,480 --> 00:09:28,220
 I've been in those moments, maybe you have too,

189
00:09:28,220 --> 00:09:32,460
 where love immediately shifts a very difficult conversation,

190
00:09:32,460 --> 00:09:36,540
 where love brings new hope into what was thought

191
00:09:36,540 --> 00:09:40,620
 to be a lost cause, where love actually changes

192
00:09:40,620 --> 00:09:43,340
 the dynamics of a relationship in a moment

193
00:09:43,340 --> 00:09:47,020
 or perhaps where love actually bridges the divide

194
00:09:47,020 --> 00:09:50,820
 of hatred or ignorance when we are swept up

195
00:09:50,820 --> 00:09:54,100
 in those moments of love, we know that the world

196
00:09:54,100 --> 00:09:57,060
 can actually change, we know that those moments

197
00:09:57,060 --> 00:09:59,620
 of love shift and change things in a way that,

198
00:09:59,620 --> 00:10:04,020
 like I say, no computer can ever predict or ever do.

199
00:10:04,020 --> 00:10:06,220
 And the reality is also in the reverse.

200
00:10:06,220 --> 00:10:11,220
 You see, strip love from us and we become less than human.

201
00:10:11,220 --> 00:10:14,460
 I would say we become programmable animals

202
00:10:14,460 --> 00:10:19,460
 that are broken and controlled, but place love within us

203
00:10:19,460 --> 00:10:23,340
 and we become the very creatures that we have been created

204
00:10:23,340 --> 00:10:28,340
 to be, human beings filled with vision and imagination

205
00:10:28,340 --> 00:10:32,020
 and passion and creativity and hope.

206
00:10:32,020 --> 00:10:38,300
 And if this is who we've truly been created to be

207
00:10:38,300 --> 00:10:42,220
 and if love is the rawest and most natural form

208
00:10:42,220 --> 00:10:45,280
 of our expression of what it means to be human,

209
00:10:45,280 --> 00:10:48,900
 could it be, therefore, that as the world embraces

210
00:10:48,900 --> 00:10:52,420
 more of an AI future, this is an opportunity

211
00:10:52,420 --> 00:10:57,420
 for the world to actually become more in love with God?

212
00:10:57,420 --> 00:11:01,420
 Because if it is love that is gonna set us aside

213
00:11:01,420 --> 00:11:04,340
 from the computers around us, then maybe we should

214
00:11:04,340 --> 00:11:08,260
 be connecting into the source of that love more than ever.

215
00:11:08,260 --> 00:11:10,200
 The Bible's very clear where that source comes from.

216
00:11:10,200 --> 00:11:13,260
 It says, God is love.

217
00:11:13,260 --> 00:11:16,420
 It doesn't say God does love, it doesn't say God

218
00:11:16,420 --> 00:11:20,820
 has this kind of, you know, sort of program to love things.

219
00:11:20,820 --> 00:11:23,020
 It says the actual very nature and essence

220
00:11:23,020 --> 00:11:27,220
 of who God is is love and because he is love,

221
00:11:27,220 --> 00:11:29,860
 he has first loved us.

222
00:11:29,860 --> 00:11:32,260
 And because he's first loved us, our love then

223
00:11:32,260 --> 00:11:34,860
 is a response to the love that's been placed

224
00:11:34,860 --> 00:11:36,620
 within us from him.

225
00:11:36,620 --> 00:11:39,620
 And if it is love that makes us the most naturally human

226
00:11:39,620 --> 00:11:42,260
 than we can possibly be and if in an AI future

227
00:11:42,260 --> 00:11:45,740
 we wanna retain our humanity, then it follows, does it not,

228
00:11:45,740 --> 00:11:47,580
 that we need to be connecting into the source

229
00:11:47,580 --> 00:11:49,860
 of where that love comes from.

230
00:11:49,860 --> 00:11:53,820
 I'm excited that the future that may well get more AI

231
00:11:53,820 --> 00:11:56,820
 is an opportunity for the church to rise up and say,

232
00:11:56,820 --> 00:11:59,820
 hey, there's one who is able to give us

233
00:11:59,820 --> 00:12:02,660
 what no computer ever can.

234
00:12:02,660 --> 00:12:05,240
 Love like that remains.

235
00:12:05,240 --> 00:12:08,620
 Which is fascinating because although Paul,

236
00:12:08,620 --> 00:12:10,980
 the apostle Paul, writing to the church in Corinth

237
00:12:10,980 --> 00:12:15,580
 had no idea about AI whatsoever, he saw a church

238
00:12:15,580 --> 00:12:18,420
 that was struggling to truly love.

239
00:12:18,420 --> 00:12:20,620
 In fact, he saw a church that was actually fighting

240
00:12:20,620 --> 00:12:22,580
 each other, a church that was actually treating

241
00:12:22,580 --> 00:12:25,220
 each other incredibly poorly and so he decides

242
00:12:25,220 --> 00:12:27,740
 to write to them in the heart of his letter,

243
00:12:27,740 --> 00:12:30,940
 chapters 12, 13, and 14 of 1 Corinthians

244
00:12:30,940 --> 00:12:33,980
 and talk to them about their attitudes and the behaviors

245
00:12:33,980 --> 00:12:37,340
 and the ways in which they were expressing their humanity

246
00:12:37,340 --> 00:12:40,340
 towards one another and in chapter 12 and 14,

247
00:12:40,340 --> 00:12:42,540
 he talks about some of the ways within their church

248
00:12:42,540 --> 00:12:45,660
 community they were expressing their humanity

249
00:12:45,660 --> 00:12:48,380
 through both their natural gifts and spiritual gifts

250
00:12:48,380 --> 00:12:51,420
 and right in between those two chapters in chapter 13,

251
00:12:51,420 --> 00:12:52,740
 he actually begins to say to them,

252
00:12:52,740 --> 00:12:55,780
 but you need to understand that if you try to express

253
00:12:55,780 --> 00:13:00,180
 your humanity without love, then you're not contributing

254
00:13:00,180 --> 00:13:03,380
 anything to this world, no matter how great your gifts are,

255
00:13:03,380 --> 00:13:05,860
 no matter how amazing the things that you might be doing

